on a new book.

237
00:18:25,572 --> 00:18:27,538
I'm nothing if not
a big old octopus.

238
00:18:27,540 --> 00:18:27,538
An octopus.

239
00:18:30,142 --> 00:18:33,344
One arm still
wrapped around <i> o lost,</i>

240
00:18:33,346 --> 00:18:36,280
while another one
sneaks over here
through the briny deep

241
00:18:36,282 --> 00:18:38,316
to write the new book.

242
00:18:38,318 --> 00:18:40,518
I guess you could say
I'm... I'm tentacular.

243
00:18:42,221 --> 00:18:43,254
What's the new one about?

244
00:18:44,289 --> 00:18:45,656
It's about America.

245
00:18:48,260 --> 00:18:50,862
All of it.
I'm trying to
capture everything.

246
00:18:50,864 --> 00:18:53,397
Every city and village

247
00:18:53,399 --> 00:18:56,734
and stone and leaf
and man and child.

248
00:18:56,736 --> 00:19:00,438
And every farm and flower,
every river.

249
00:19:00,440 --> 00:19:03,207
It's about
the one acetylene torch,

250
00:19:03,209 --> 00:19:07,211
white, bright truth
that burns in the heart
of every man in this country.

251
00:19:07,213 --> 00:19:09,914
And that is the search
for a true father.

252
00:19:11,750 --> 00:19:14,152
I don't mean
biological father.

253
00:19:14,154 --> 00:19:15,553
I'm not talking
about sperm.

254
00:19:17,357 --> 00:19:20,791
I mean, I search for the need
of a father of our spirit.

255
00:19:20,793 --> 00:19:23,227
It's about every single thing
that makes this country great.

256
00:19:23,229 --> 00:19:24,529
It's mammoth!

257
00:19:25,899 --> 00:19:29,167
Max says

258
00:19:29,169 --> 00:19:31,469
the only ideas
worth writing about
are the big ideas.

259
00:19:31,471 --> 00:19:33,871
Big ideas,
fewer words.

260
00:19:33,873 --> 00:19:35,706
You see,
I'm lost without him.

261
00:19:35,708 --> 00:19:37,942
Aren't we all?
You know I'm a writer, too?

262
00:19:37,944 --> 00:19:40,211
That so?

263
00:19:40,213 --> 00:19:42,213
Max didn't tell you?
Mmm.

264
00:19:42,215 --> 00:19:45,483
I've been working on a play
for quite some time now.

265
00:19:45,485 --> 00:19:48,219
It's about pauline,
Napoleon's sister.

266
00:19:48,221 --> 00:19:50,688
Historical pageant,
is it?

267
00:19:50,690 --> 00:19:53,691
Well, it's attempting
to be more modern.

268
00:19:53,693 --> 00:19:57,662
I wrote a play once.
It was not a happy experience,
i can tell you that.

269
00:19:57,664 --> 00:20:00,865
I found it
an anemic form,

270
00:20:00,867 --> 00:20:03,668
lacking the multi-colored
cloak of prose.

271
00:20:03,670 --> 00:20:06,771
So I dumped the form
and returned to my novels.

272
00:20:06,773 --> 00:20:08,573
Do you have a title
for your new book?

273
00:20:08,575 --> 00:20:11,242
Your daddy and i
have considered a bunch.

274
00:20:11,244 --> 00:20:15,446
Right now we're thinking about
<i> of time and the river.</i>

275
00:20:15,448 --> 00:20:19,350
"The river" 'cause
that word just reminds
me of my father.

276
00:20:21,687 --> 00:20:24,956
The river running
away from his door
and right back again.

277
00:20:24,958 --> 00:20:26,824
That sounds like
quite a long book.

278
00:20:32,431 --> 00:20:34,532
Don't say that, aline.

279
00:20:34,534 --> 00:20:36,467
I'll see you tomorrow.

280
00:20:37,736 --> 00:20:39,670
Keep yourself ready for me.

281
00:20:40,672 --> 00:20:43,441
Goodnight. Goodnight.

282
00:20:44,710 --> 00:20:46,477
This should
do you nicely.

283
00:20:48,513 --> 00:20:50,314
I'll see you
in the morning.

284
00:20:52,351 --> 00:20:53,317
Max.

285
00:20:56,555 --> 00:20:57,922
Thank you
for tonight.

286
00:20:59,691 --> 00:21:02,593
I hope I didn't
offend anyone.

287
00:21:02,595 --> 00:21:04,695
I so want your family
to like me.

288
00:21:04,697 --> 00:21:05,763
Don't worry.
Of course not.

289
00:21:05,765 --> 00:21:07,465
I'm not a circus animal.

290
00:21:08,900 --> 00:21:11,702
See, I know I seem
like a freak.

291
00:21:11,704 --> 00:21:13,504
Too loud,

292
00:21:13,506 --> 00:21:16,774
too grandiose,
not quite real.

293
00:21:18,510 --> 00:21:20,478
That's who I am.

294
00:21:20,480 --> 00:21:22,780
That's how I got
out of asheville,
by making noise.

295
00:21:22,782 --> 00:21:24,415
I thrashed my way out.

296
00:21:25,751 --> 00:21:29,053
But I feel things
like a real person.

297
00:21:30,022 --> 00:21:30,988
So...

298
00:21:34,293 --> 00:21:38,696
...from caliban's heart,
i say this.

299
00:21:38,698 --> 00:21:42,667
In all my life,
well, till I met you,
i never had a friend.

300
00:22:19,338 --> 00:22:22,540
If we nail down
Ben's death today,

301
00:22:22,542 --> 00:22:24,875
then, hell,
we're within hollering
distance of the end.

302
00:22:25,777 --> 00:22:27,111
Aline!

303
00:22:28,848 --> 00:22:30,481
Max.

304
00:22:30,483 --> 00:22:34,518
Let me introduce you.
This is Mrs. Bernstein.

305
00:22:34,520 --> 00:22:35,886
How do you do?

306
00:22:35,888 --> 00:22:38,122
Mr. Perkins.

307
00:22:38,124 --> 00:22:40,758
Tom has told me
so much about you.

308
00:22:40,760 --> 00:22:43,894
She's the first person
who told me my writing
was worth anything.

309
00:22:43,896 --> 00:22:46,597
Hell, she's the whole
reason for our book.

310
00:22:46,599 --> 00:22:48,466
I thank you for that.

311
00:22:48,468 --> 00:22:49,700
We were expected
last night.

312
00:22:49,702 --> 00:22:50,968
Oh, I told you...

313
00:22:50,970 --> 00:22:52,603
It was embarrassing
for me.

314
00:22:52,605 --> 00:22:53,838
You know I hate
those theatrical affairs.

315
00:22:53,840 --> 00:22:55,072
And you know
i didn't want
to go alone.

316
00:22:55,074 --> 00:22:56,907
If you'll excuse me.

317
00:22:56,909 --> 00:22:59,110
All those actors
make me feel awkward.
You know that!

318
00:22:59,112 --> 00:23:00,778
I told you i
wasn't gonna come.

319
00:23:00,780 --> 00:23:03,914
We will
continue this alone.

320
00:23:04,883 --> 00:23:06,417
I'll come by
around 2:00.

321
00:23:06,419 --> 00:23:08,085
2:00. Perfect. Thanks.

322
00:23:08,087 --> 00:23:09,854
Come on.

323
00:23:09,856 --> 00:23:12,123
Good day,
Mr. Perkins.

324
00:23:12,125 --> 00:23:13,691
You are so mad at me.

325
00:23:13,693 --> 00:23:14,959
No, I'm not.
I'm not mad at you.

326
00:23:24,403 --> 00:23:25,403
There it is.
Hmm.

327
00:23:29,007 --> 00:23:31,942
This is our last chance
before we go to the printer.

328
00:23:31,944 --> 00:23:34,945
So I'll ask you again.

329
00:23:34,947 --> 00:23:36,847
Have you thought
about another title?

330
00:23:37,883 --> 00:23:39,116
You'll hate it.

331
00:23:39,118 --> 00:23:40,084
Try me.

332
00:24:15,921 --> 00:24:18,956
Now, I'm
a scribner's bestseller,

333
00:24:18,958 --> 00:24:22,226
I figured I deserve
a little of the high life.

334
00:24:22,228 --> 00:24:23,928
Say it again, Max.

335
00:24:23,930 --> 00:24:25,763
Fifteen thousand
copies this month.
Oh.

336
00:24:27,666 --> 00:24:30,201
Aline,
you hear that?
Mmm-hmm.

337
00:24:30,203 --> 00:24:32,903
Not even the economy
of the entire country

338
00:24:32,905 --> 00:24:36,006
crumbling around our ankles
is hurting my book.

339
00:24:36,008 --> 00:24:38,943
Have you read
tom's book,
Mrs. Bernstein?

340
00:24:38,945 --> 00:24:42,079
Yes, Mrs. Perkins,
it's dedicated to me.

341
00:24:42,081 --> 00:24:45,182
I wouldn't have
been able to do it
without my sweet jewess.

342
00:24:45,184 --> 00:24:47,585
She bought the paper
and the pencils.

343
00:24:47,587 --> 00:24:49,487
- And paid for the typist.
- That's enough.

344
00:24:49,489 --> 00:24:50,754
That's enough.
She put a roof
over my head

345
00:24:50,756 --> 00:24:52,556
and food in my
prodigious belly.

346
00:24:52,558 --> 00:24:53,924
Hell, y'all know how
much I love to eat.

347
00:24:53,926 --> 00:24:55,926
You must be very
proud of the book,

348
00:24:55,928 --> 00:24:58,095
to see all your
faith rewarded.

349
00:24:58,097 --> 00:25:00,130
Our faith.

350
00:25:00,132 --> 00:25:02,900
It's our faith now,
isn't it, Mr. Perkins?

351
00:25:02,902 --> 00:25:04,034
Tom couldn't have
done it without you.

352
00:25:04,036 --> 00:25:06,704
That's not true.

353
00:25:06,706 --> 00:25:08,973
You needn't play
at humble pie with me.

354
00:25:08,975 --> 00:25:11,775
Tom speaks of
your contribution
with such passion.

355
00:25:13,645 --> 00:25:15,946
He really can't seem
to stop talking about you.

356
00:25:15,948 --> 00:25:18,649
"Max says this.
Max says that."

357
00:25:18,651 --> 00:25:20,718
Easy, girl.
Easy, girl.
"Max, Max, Max."

358
00:25:20,720 --> 00:25:23,587
No, we should
give Mr. Perkins
all of the credit.

359
00:25:23,589 --> 00:25:26,690
I mean, after all, he is
the genius who made all
of your dreams come true.

360
00:25:26,692 --> 00:25:29,159
He's the one who shaped
that massive collection
of words into a...

361
00:25:29,161 --> 00:25:33,163
Into a marketable
bestseller,

362
00:25:33,165 --> 00:25:36,133
putting it into
the eager hands
of readers everywhere.

363
00:25:36,135 --> 00:25:39,236
I mean, that is
quite a triumph
for Mr. Perkins, hmm?

364
00:25:42,607 --> 00:25:46,076
The work is tom's.
He deserves to enjoy it.

365
00:25:46,078 --> 00:25:47,311
Really?
Is that what
tom deserves?

366
00:25:47,313 --> 00:25:48,913
Leave Max alone.

367
00:25:48,915 --> 00:25:51,582
I'm not speaking to you,
I'm speaking to your elder.

368
00:25:51,584 --> 00:25:54,218
You should learn
to trust your elders.
They know what's best.

369
00:25:54,220 --> 00:25:56,554
They should also
behave in a manner
appropriate to their years.

370
00:25:57,856 --> 00:26:00,558
You're Thomas wolfe?

371
00:26:00,560 --> 00:26:02,960
I'm reading your book.
It's a masterpiece.

372
00:26:02,962 --> 00:26:04,161
Is it, now?

373
00:26:04,163 --> 00:26:06,297
Very much.

374
00:26:06,299 --> 00:26:09,099
Look, um, I have
some friends who are
dying to meet you.

375
00:26:09,101 --> 00:26:11,735
You don't mind
if I steal him
for a tick or two?

376
00:26:11,737 --> 00:26:13,737
Of course you don't.
Oh, not at all.

377
00:26:13,739 --> 00:26:15,306
After you.
Okay. I'm Willow.

378
00:26:15,308 --> 00:26:16,273
Nice to meet you.
What a pleasure.

379
00:26:20,312 --> 00:26:21,979
Good evening.

380
00:26:21,981 --> 00:26:23,948
This is Thomas wolfe.
No, it's my pleasure.

381
00:26:23,950 --> 00:26:25,115
Good evening.
Nice to meet you.

382
00:26:50,909 --> 00:26:53,644
You don't know what they're
like, the state asylums.

383
00:26:54,346 --> 00:26:55,646
Grotesque.

384
00:26:57,215 --> 00:27:00,084
I don't have the words.
There...

385
00:27:00,086 --> 00:27:03,120
There are no words
in my lexicon.

386
00:27:03,122 --> 00:27:05,756
One word, no flourishes.
Grotesque.

387
00:27:08,193 --> 00:27:10,894
The screaming is
constant and so...

388
00:27:12,163 --> 00:27:13,897
Desolate.

389
00:27:15,266 --> 00:27:17,001
They don't have
enough toilets.

390
00:27:19,204 --> 00:27:22,072
I can't let Zelda
stay in such a place.

391
00:27:22,074 --> 00:27:22,072
I know.

392
00:27:25,343 --> 00:27:27,711
But private asylums
are expensive

393
00:27:31,216 --> 00:27:33,350
and I know <i> gatsby</i>
didn't make any money.

394
00:27:36,688 --> 00:27:38,689
But I'm up
against it, Max.

395
00:27:38,691 --> 00:27:40,858
Scribner's can't give you
any more advances.

396
00:27:44,929 --> 00:27:47,164
<i> The post</i> won't even take
any more of my stories.

397
00:27:50,301 --> 00:27:52,670
I guess I could go back
to Hollywood and give
that another try.

398
00:27:52,672 --> 00:27:54,772
I hope you don't do that.

399
00:27:54,774 --> 00:27:55,873
Why?
You're a novelist.

400
00:27:58,076 --> 00:27:58,976
Not anymore.

401
00:28:02,180 --> 00:28:04,114
I should have died
when I was 24.

402
00:28:06,351 --> 00:28:07,885
Right after
<i> this side of paradise.</i>

403
00:28:11,056 --> 00:28:12,289
Did you get that
book I sent you?

404
00:28:13,425 --> 00:28:14,958
Which?

405
00:28:14,960 --> 00:28:17,461
General Grant's memoirs.

406
00:28:17,463 --> 00:28:19,396
Do you know how he
came to write them?

407
00:28:22,067 --> 00:28:23,400
This is interesting.

408
00:28:25,003 --> 00:28:28,105
He was dying
of throat cancer

409
00:28:30,175 --> 00:28:33,377
and he wanted to leave
something behind
for his family,

410
00:28:33,379 --> 00:28:35,979
so he started writing
his autobiography.

411
00:28:38,383 --> 00:28:40,384
He worked every day
for hours and hours.

412
00:28:41,753 --> 00:28:44,455
He was in great pain,
anguish,

413
00:28:44,457 --> 00:28:46,990
but he just
kept on writing.

414
00:28:49,094 --> 00:28:51,729
And in the end, he produced
the most astounding book.

415
00:28:53,965 --> 00:28:55,299
So very beautiful.

416
00:28:59,871 --> 00:29:01,905
Just a little velvet
to see you through.

417
00:29:12,383 --> 00:29:13,784
I'll write you
a great book.

418
00:29:15,086 --> 00:29:16,019
I know.

419
00:29:59,531 --> 00:30:00,898
Mrs. Perkins.

420
00:30:02,367 --> 00:30:03,367
Mrs. Bernstein.

421
00:30:05,537 --> 00:30:08,138
Hello.

422
00:30:08,140 --> 00:30:09,473
You're designing
this production?

423
00:30:10,041 --> 00:30:11,008
Yes.

424
00:30:11,910 --> 00:30:13,544
Me and all the lost boys.

425
00:30:16,381 --> 00:30:17,447
We know a few of them,
don't we?

426
00:30:20,518 --> 00:30:25,155
You didn't know him
when he was young.
He was fresh out of Harvard

427
00:30:25,157 --> 00:30:28,926
and he was all ready
to carve up the world.

428
00:30:28,928 --> 00:30:31,128
He was unlike anyone
I'd ever met.

429
00:30:31,130 --> 00:30:31,962
I understand.

430
00:30:32,864 --> 00:30:36,099
I don't think
that you do.

431
00:30:36,101 --> 00:30:39,269
You see, my husband
is a very kind man, but
he's a man without color.

432
00:30:40,572 --> 00:30:44,308
He's a man
of wall street
and numbers.

433
00:30:45,511 --> 00:30:47,311
I don't
understand numbers.

434
00:30:47,313 --> 00:30:49,346
You have children,
Mrs. Bernstein?

435
00:30:49,348 --> 00:30:50,314
Yes.

436
00:30:51,182 --> 00:30:53,083
A daughter and a son.

437
00:30:54,519 --> 00:30:55,986
They're grown.

438
00:30:58,857 --> 00:31:01,024
I did a foolish thing
when I fell in love
with tom,

439
00:31:01,026 --> 00:31:02,359
but I can't help
how I feel.

440
00:31:02,361 --> 00:31:05,062
My heart was touched.

441
00:31:06,531 --> 00:31:08,432
At the very time
in my life

442
00:31:08,434 --> 00:31:10,267
when everything beautiful
was falling away

443
00:31:10,269 --> 00:31:13,270
and no one needed me,
i met tom.

444
00:31:13,272 --> 00:31:16,173
And tom made me
feel beautiful again.

445
00:31:20,245 --> 00:31:22,613
But I know now
I've lost him
to your husband.

446
00:31:26,251 --> 00:31:27,551
Mrs. Bernstein.

447
00:31:31,556 --> 00:31:36,260
My husband always
wanted a son

448
00:31:36,262 --> 00:31:39,529
more than anything
in the world.

449
00:31:39,531 --> 00:31:42,966
We reached a point
when we realized that
wasn't going to happen.

450
00:31:42,968 --> 00:31:44,034
And then he met tom.

451
00:31:46,170 --> 00:31:48,305
I can't let him go.

452
00:31:48,307 --> 00:31:50,240
Aline, go home
to your family.

453
00:31:52,243 --> 00:31:55,979
They need you.
Tom doesn't.

454
00:31:55,981 --> 00:31:59,383
Family,
husband,
dignity.

455
00:32:01,352 --> 00:32:03,320
I gave that
all up for him.

456
00:32:12,430 --> 00:32:13,363
Tom.

457
00:32:14,132 --> 00:32:15,332
Come in.

458
00:32:18,202 --> 00:32:19,069
Tom?

459
00:32:19,671 --> 00:32:21,271
I have it.

460
00:32:21,273 --> 00:32:22,439
You have it?

461
00:32:23,474 --> 00:32:24,474
The new book.

462
00:32:27,312 --> 00:32:28,211
With you?

463
00:32:29,180 --> 00:32:30,247
Yes.

464
00:32:32,517 --> 00:32:33,684
Well, let's have it.

465
00:32:35,987 --> 00:32:37,387
Bring it in, guys.

466
00:32:39,991 --> 00:32:41,024
Put it down there.

467
00:32:45,129 --> 00:32:48,231
This is
<i> of time and the river?</i>

468
00:32:55,139 --> 00:32:56,239
Here you go.
Thank you, sir.

469
00:33:12,590 --> 00:33:13,657
Well done.

470
00:33:18,998 --> 00:33:20,497
Now, go home
and get some sleep.

471
00:33:20,499 --> 00:33:22,099
I need you...
Let me read it.

472
00:33:23,234 --> 00:33:25,569
Read it kindly.
Please?

473
00:34:04,475 --> 00:34:08,078
If we work every day
in the evening,
when we won't be disturbed,

474
00:34:09,247 --> 00:34:10,547
we can do it.

475
00:34:11,649 --> 00:34:14,251
How long?
Nine months.

476
00:34:14,253 --> 00:34:16,720
If you work hard and
if you resist the temptation
to add much more.

477
00:34:17,822 --> 00:34:19,689
I have to be able
to add more.

478
00:34:19,691 --> 00:34:23,493
Tom, the book
is 5,000 pages long.

479
00:34:24,062 --> 00:34:24,795
Point taken.

480
00:34:28,699 --> 00:34:31,501
Now, to begin,
on page one.

481
00:34:31,503 --> 00:34:34,438
Oh, lord. Page one?

482
00:34:34,440 --> 00:34:37,474
Now, look here,
you've given 80
pages to Eugene

483
00:34:37,476 --> 00:34:40,243
on the platform
before the train arrives.

484
00:34:40,245 --> 00:34:44,281
That is, perhaps,
gilding the Lily a bit
as to suspense?

485
00:34:44,283 --> 00:34:45,315
I mean, I'll only wait
so long for a train.

