00:50:08,439 --> 00:50:10,272
I see your knees moving.

733
00:50:16,780 --> 00:50:18,447
Come on, Max!
Feel it!

734
00:50:22,586 --> 00:50:23,486
Nice.

735
00:50:44,107 --> 00:50:45,808
You see those two
fine ladies over there?

736
00:50:47,110 --> 00:50:50,146
Subtle.
Max, be subtle.

737
00:50:50,148 --> 00:50:50,780
At the bar?
Mmm-hmm.

738
00:50:53,650 --> 00:50:56,619
Let's go over there,
say hello.

739
00:50:56,621 --> 00:51:00,122
Come on!
Let's have some fun.
I can't. I can't.

740
00:51:00,124 --> 00:51:02,491
They're working girls, Max.
It doesn't count.

741
00:51:04,227 --> 00:51:06,395
Yes, tom, it does.

742
00:51:09,466 --> 00:51:10,332
Well, you don't mind
if I...
No.

743
00:51:24,748 --> 00:51:27,716
Hell, I never know
when to stop, do I?

744
00:51:32,322 --> 00:51:33,322
- Three bourbons!
- You got it.

745
00:51:33,324 --> 00:51:35,691
One, two, three.

746
00:51:37,427 --> 00:51:39,328
And you, too.

747
00:51:40,831 --> 00:51:42,565
I saw you looking at me.

748
00:51:46,403 --> 00:51:48,604
Don't worry,
i ain't gonna
leave you out.

749
00:51:54,678 --> 00:51:57,746
I'm gonna want
the both of you.
All right?

750
00:51:57,748 --> 00:51:58,814
Let's have a drink.

751
00:52:24,875 --> 00:52:26,675
<i> I'll tell you</i>
<i> one thing, my friend.</i>

752
00:52:26,677 --> 00:52:29,245
You wouldn't do
this to Hemingway.

753
00:52:29,247 --> 00:52:33,716
You wouldn't do this
to Fitzgerald, not to your
two goddamn sacred cows!

754
00:52:33,718 --> 00:52:35,818
Every word they write
is golden genius!

755
00:52:35,820 --> 00:52:37,686
Stop it!

756
00:52:37,688 --> 00:52:39,688
I bring you stuff
wrenched right
from my guts

757
00:52:39,690 --> 00:52:41,390
and you tell me
it doesn't fit.

758
00:52:41,392 --> 00:52:42,758
That's enough.
Go home.

759
00:52:43,393 --> 00:52:44,793
What?

760
00:52:44,795 --> 00:52:46,862
Go home.
Go to sleep.

761
00:52:46,864 --> 00:52:49,532
No. No, no.

762
00:52:50,200 --> 00:52:51,934
I'm sorry.

763
00:52:51,936 --> 00:52:56,205
Please, don't make me go home.
Let me come home with you.

764
00:52:56,207 --> 00:52:58,207
We... we can still
make the 9:02.

765
00:52:58,209 --> 00:53:00,276
No, I'm exhausted
and you're drunk.

766
00:53:00,278 --> 00:53:01,810
We'll pick up
tomorrow.
No.

767
00:53:01,812 --> 00:53:02,645
You heard him, tom.

768
00:53:04,881 --> 00:53:06,248
Come home.

769
00:53:08,285 --> 00:53:10,452
I'll pay
for the taxi.

770
00:53:10,454 --> 00:53:12,788
What the hell
are you doing here?

771
00:53:12,790 --> 00:53:16,325
I can make you dinner.
I'll pay for that, too.

772
00:53:16,327 --> 00:53:20,196
Get out of here.
I'm working.

773
00:53:20,198 --> 00:53:23,365
Mr. Perkins has informed
you you're not working
anymore tonight

774
00:53:23,367 --> 00:53:24,934
so come on, come with me.

775
00:53:24,936 --> 00:53:26,602
Mrs. Bernstein...

776
00:53:26,604 --> 00:53:28,704
- Don't touch me!
- For heaven's sake.

777
00:53:28,706 --> 00:53:30,839
You stay there.
Jesus, aline!

778
00:53:32,342 --> 00:53:33,709
- Come.
- Aline.

779
00:53:36,246 --> 00:53:36,879
You don't want
to see me?

780
00:53:38,815 --> 00:53:39,848
Fine!

781
00:53:40,483 --> 00:53:41,483
Fine!

782
00:53:43,420 --> 00:53:45,588
You will never
have to see me again.

783
00:53:45,590 --> 00:53:46,555
Aline.

784
00:53:47,824 --> 00:53:49,258
Hmm?
What are you doing?

785
00:53:51,294 --> 00:53:51,894
What the hell
are you doing?

786
00:53:53,496 --> 00:53:55,331
- Aline!
- No!

787
00:53:55,333 --> 00:53:56,832
- Stop it.
- No!

788
00:53:56,834 --> 00:53:58,434
- Spit 'em!
- No!

789
00:53:58,436 --> 00:53:59,969
Spit 'em!

790
00:53:59,971 --> 00:54:02,905
No.
You spit 'em out.
Spit 'em out.

791
00:54:02,907 --> 00:54:04,873
Spit 'em out!
You spit it out.

792
00:54:07,777 --> 00:54:11,413
Stop now, aline.
My love.

793
00:54:11,415 --> 00:54:14,350
My love, my angel.
Stop now.

794
00:54:14,352 --> 00:54:17,886
All right.
All right. All right.

795
00:54:17,888 --> 00:54:19,755
Show me your
strength, darling.

796
00:54:19,757 --> 00:54:21,257
Look at me. Look at me!

797
00:54:21,858 --> 00:54:23,759
Show me your strength.

798
00:54:23,761 --> 00:54:26,395
Hmm? Come on.
Come on.

799
00:54:26,397 --> 00:54:30,933
All right. Come on.
Come on. That's it.

800
00:54:30,935 --> 00:54:32,935
All right. All right.

801
00:54:34,371 --> 00:54:34,370
Mr. Perkins...

802
00:54:38,942 --> 00:54:41,610
I know things such as this
don't happen here

803
00:54:41,612 --> 00:54:43,946
on the fifth floor.
I apologize.

804
00:54:43,948 --> 00:54:47,349
That's not necessary.
If you'll excuse me.

805
00:54:47,351 --> 00:54:48,651
Wait up, wait up.
I'll be right there.

806
00:54:48,653 --> 00:54:49,918
No, tom, really!

807
00:54:49,920 --> 00:54:52,621
Just give me
a second.

808
00:54:52,623 --> 00:54:55,524
I'll see you at home.
All right.

809
00:54:55,526 --> 00:54:56,592
All right.

810
00:55:10,440 --> 00:55:13,075
You were right,
about the cut.

811
00:55:13,077 --> 00:55:14,977
Sorry about being
such a bear.

812
00:55:18,381 --> 00:55:21,450
Don't you think
you should go
with Mrs. Bernstein?

813
00:55:21,452 --> 00:55:24,486
Hell, she was just
being theatrical.

814
00:55:26,022 --> 00:55:28,657
All right,
so we forget
about the cut.

815
00:55:28,659 --> 00:55:31,060
Let's go on
to Eugene
in London.

816
00:55:32,929 --> 00:55:36,498
"He thought of the huge
smoky web of London
with the same joy,

817
00:55:36,500 --> 00:55:39,101
"of the suave
potent ale he could get
in one place there,

818
00:55:39,103 --> 00:55:41,470
"of its squares and
ancient courts..."

819
00:55:48,878 --> 00:55:50,813
Daddy!

820
00:55:50,815 --> 00:55:51,880
Daddy!

821
00:55:58,988 --> 00:56:00,089
Hurry up.

822
00:56:00,091 --> 00:56:01,557
Hi, daddy.
Hello, duck.

823
00:56:01,559 --> 00:56:03,859
Ooh!

824
00:56:03,861 --> 00:56:05,494
Daddy, I caught
a rainbow trout.
Nine inches!

825
00:56:05,496 --> 00:56:07,396
You go help
your sisters.

826
00:56:12,702 --> 00:56:14,737
You would not
believe the amount...

827
00:56:17,040 --> 00:56:18,707
Maxwell, please.

828
00:57:02,852 --> 00:57:03,685
Tom.

829
00:57:05,922 --> 00:57:07,022
Tom!

830
00:57:09,859 --> 00:57:10,959
It's done.

831
00:57:13,129 --> 00:57:14,496
Done?

832
00:57:14,498 --> 00:57:15,664
Stop writing.

833
00:57:17,767 --> 00:57:20,502
Gather all your papers
and bring them in tomorrow.

834
00:57:20,504 --> 00:57:21,703
Can you do that?

835
00:57:22,605 --> 00:57:24,106
Can you do that?

836
00:57:24,108 --> 00:57:24,973
Yes.

837
00:57:28,144 --> 00:57:31,914
We finish editing this month.
We go to press in April.

838
00:57:34,050 --> 00:57:35,684
We publish in October.

839
00:57:37,587 --> 00:57:40,088
Look at me and say yes.

840
00:57:46,129 --> 00:57:47,062
Yes.

841
00:58:30,607 --> 00:58:33,208
Hmm. Shoot.
Mmm-hmm.

842
00:58:39,215 --> 00:58:40,916
I think I'll go rambling.

843
00:58:41,718 --> 00:58:42,885
Maybe Europe.

844
00:58:44,587 --> 00:58:48,056
Don't want to be around
when the reviews come out.

845
00:58:52,028 --> 00:58:52,995
What?

846
00:58:56,132 --> 00:58:58,534
There's one paragraph
i have to add to the book.

847
00:58:58,536 --> 00:59:00,269
By god!
I have to add it.

848
00:59:00,271 --> 00:59:00,269
If you start
adding paragraphs,
we're sunk.

849
00:59:00,271 --> 00:59:04,206
One paragraph will lead
to two and then we'll be
here for another year.

850
00:59:04,208 --> 00:59:06,675
Shall I read it
to you?

851
00:59:06,677 --> 00:59:08,176
It goes
at the very front.

852
00:59:13,583 --> 00:59:18,921
"This book is dedicated
to Maxwell evarts Perkins.

853
00:59:21,758 --> 00:59:24,660
"A brave and honest man

854
00:59:26,930 --> 00:59:29,565
"who stuck to
the writer of this book

855
00:59:29,567 --> 00:59:33,335
"through times of
bitter hopelessness.

856
00:59:35,638 --> 00:59:37,606
"The author hopes

857
00:59:37,608 --> 00:59:41,243
"this book will
prove worthy of him."

858
00:59:46,883 --> 00:59:48,984
I wish you wouldn't.
Oh.

859
00:59:50,286 --> 00:59:52,354
Why?
Editors should be
anonymous.

860
00:59:54,657 --> 00:59:55,924
More than that,

861
00:59:57,894 --> 00:59:59,861
there's always the fear

862
00:59:59,863 --> 01:00:01,163
that I deformed your book.

863
01:00:04,734 --> 01:00:06,234
Who's to say
it wasn't the way
it was meant to be

864
01:00:06,236 --> 01:00:07,970
when you first
brought it in?

865
01:00:09,672 --> 01:00:11,006
<i> War and peace.</i>

866
01:00:12,141 --> 01:00:13,175
Not just <i> war.</i>

867
01:00:13,177 --> 01:00:15,644
Max.

868
01:00:15,646 --> 01:00:17,879
That's what we editors
lose sleep over,
you know?

869
01:00:19,749 --> 01:00:21,617
Are we really making
books better?

870
01:00:28,324 --> 01:00:29,891
Or just making
them different?

871
01:00:49,078 --> 01:00:50,178
Morning, Mr. Perkins.

872
01:01:26,916 --> 01:01:30,419
Miss wyckoff,
where would we find
Mr. wolfe at the moment?

873
01:01:30,421 --> 01:01:31,153
<i> He's in Paris, sir.</i>

874
01:01:39,195 --> 01:01:42,831
<i> "Magnificent reviews.</i>
<i> Full of praise.</i>

875
01:01:42,833 --> 01:01:45,834
<i> "Congratulations,</i>
<i> you've done it again.</i>
<i> Max."</i>

876
01:01:50,907 --> 01:01:54,943
<i> "I can face</i>
<i> blunt fact better than</i>
<i> damnable incertitude.</i>

877
01:01:54,945 --> 01:01:58,814
<i> "Give me the damn</i>
<i> straight plain truth</i>
<i> right now, damn you!</i>

878
01:01:58,816 --> 01:01:59,815
<i> "Tom."</i>

879
01:02:03,286 --> 01:02:06,154
<i> "Talked of everywhere</i>
<i> as a truly important book.</i>

880
01:02:06,156 --> 01:02:08,457
<i> "All comparisons</i>
<i> with greatest writers.</i>

881
01:02:08,459 --> 01:02:09,991
<i> "Even James Joyce."</i>

882
01:02:14,997 --> 01:02:17,132
<i> "Hell, Joyce wishes</i>
<i> he was so good."</i>

883
01:02:19,335 --> 01:02:21,770
<i> "Had to rush out</i>
<i> five editions of the book.</i>

884
01:02:21,772 --> 01:02:24,139
<i> "Thirty thousand copies.</i>

885
01:02:24,141 --> 01:02:27,008
<i> "Never seen</i>
<i> a book so talked about.</i>

886
01:02:27,010 --> 01:02:29,211
<i> "They're calling</i>
<i> you a genius again,</i>
<i> god help you.</i>

887
01:02:30,046 --> 01:02:32,380
<i> "Come home soon. Max."</i>

888
01:02:46,829 --> 01:02:48,029
Mrs. Bernstein.

889
01:02:50,032 --> 01:02:51,166
Mr. Perkins.

890
01:02:54,937 --> 01:02:56,471
What can I do for you?

891
01:02:56,473 --> 01:03:00,475
It's rather what
can I do for you,
Mr. Perkins.

892
01:03:00,477 --> 01:03:04,312
I couldn't help noticing
tom dedicated his
new book to you.

893
01:03:04,314 --> 01:03:07,415
He dedicated his
first book to me,
you will recall.

894
01:03:07,417 --> 01:03:09,451
It was a lovely sentiment

895
01:03:09,453 --> 01:03:13,188
but what he was
actually saying was,
"thank you and goodbye."

896
01:03:14,490 --> 01:03:16,124
I had served my purpose.

897
01:03:17,426 --> 01:03:20,328
And now,
you have served yours.

898
01:03:20,330 --> 01:03:22,030
"Thank you and goodbye,
Mr. Perkins."

899
01:03:22,032 --> 01:03:24,065
With respect,
Mrs. Bernstein,

900
01:03:24,067 --> 01:03:26,835
you haven't
the slightest notion
of my relationship with tom.

901
01:03:26,837 --> 01:03:26,835
And in view of that...
He makes you do things

902
01:03:26,837 --> 01:03:29,504
you never thought you'd do.
He liberates you.

903
01:03:33,476 --> 01:03:36,044
And just when
you have come
to depend upon that,

904
01:03:36,046 --> 01:03:37,379
he will leave you.

905
01:03:39,282 --> 01:03:41,283
And you will never
feel so alive again.

906
01:03:43,386 --> 01:03:46,254
I'm sorry, Mrs. Bernstein.
I know this has
been hard on you.

907
01:03:48,858 --> 01:03:50,258
Whatever pain
he's caused you,

908
01:03:50,260 --> 01:03:52,093
I can only hope
he didn't mean it.

909
01:03:52,095 --> 01:03:53,495
Can you give me his
address in Europe?

910
01:03:53,497 --> 01:03:54,963
He asked me not to.

911
01:03:54,965 --> 01:03:56,464
Can you tell me
when he's coming home?

912
01:03:56,466 --> 01:03:57,899
I don't think so.

913
01:03:57,901 --> 01:03:59,401
So,

914
01:04:01,103 --> 01:04:02,604
I don't exist anymore.

915
01:04:08,177 --> 01:04:10,912
I've been edited.

916
01:04:21,958 --> 01:04:25,193
I haven't quite decided
who I'm going to shoot yet.

917
01:04:25,195 --> 01:04:26,328
Tom,

918
01:04:26,330 --> 01:04:27,562
myself

919
01:04:30,466 --> 01:04:31,867
or you.

920
01:04:33,936 --> 01:04:35,003
Have you
a suggestion?

921
01:04:38,641 --> 01:04:42,010
Suicide seems
a bit extreme.

922
01:04:42,012 --> 01:04:43,511
And killing tom
won't help much.

923
01:04:43,513 --> 01:04:45,413
So I suppose
that leaves me.

924
01:04:46,215 --> 01:04:48,016
I suppose it does.

925
01:04:57,326 --> 01:04:59,327
You're overwriting
the scene, Mrs. Bernstein.

926
01:05:19,682 --> 01:05:21,449
We shall see,
Mr. Perkins.

927
01:05:32,695 --> 01:05:35,931
I am very sorry
for what's going
to happen to you.

928
01:05:35,933 --> 01:05:37,198
Truly, I am.

929
01:05:38,501 --> 01:05:40,235
Enjoy the time with tom
while you have it

930
01:05:40,237 --> 01:05:41,970
because after him...

931
01:05:45,275 --> 01:05:46,942
...there is a great hush.

932
01:06:01,290 --> 01:06:03,325
Hey,
good to see you.

933
01:06:09,598 --> 01:06:10,498
Max!

934
01:06:11,334 --> 01:06:12,233
Tom!

935
01:06:17,373 --> 01:06:19,441
Oh!

936
01:06:19,443 --> 01:06:21,476
Wonderful
to see you, tom.

937
01:06:21,478 --> 01:06:24,312
But we need to talk.
I have a taxi waiting.

938
01:06:24,314 --> 01:06:26,381
Heck, no!
Taxi can take
my luggage.

939
01:06:26,383 --> 01:06:29,718
No taxis or trains
or buses or automation.

940
01:06:29,720 --> 01:06:31,486
I have to ambulate.

941
01:06:31,488 --> 01:06:34,155
I have to feel
my country again.

942
01:06:34,157 --> 01:06:35,657
You go ahead.
Thank you, sir.

943
01:06:35,659 --> 01:06:38,026
You don't know how
much I missed you.

944
01:06:38,028 --> 01:06:40,662
Oh, I missed you too, tom,
but this is important.

945
01:06:40,664 --> 01:06:43,164
Aline came to the office
and she has a gun.

946
01:06:43,166 --> 01:06:44,766
An actual gun.

947
01:06:44,768 --> 01:06:46,701
Hell with her.

948
01:06:46,703 --> 01:06:48,403
I've been away
so long,

949
01:06:48,405 --> 01:06:51,706
we have to celebrate
my return to the greatest
of nations

950
01:06:51,708 --> 01:06:53,475
with all things American.

951
01:06:53,477 --> 01:06:57,112
I have to eat some wieners
and, and walk the city

952
01:06:57,114 --> 01:06:58,680
and drink us
some serious liquor.

953
01:07:01,317 --> 01:07:04,052
I mean,
can one man do it?

954
01:07:04,054 --> 01:07:06,121
Write his whole
life story fairly?

955
01:07:06,123 --> 01:07:08,323
Honestly? Like proust,

956
01:07:08,325 --> 01:07:09,491
without all the upholstery.

957
01:07:09,493 --> 01:07:11,693
Well, sure.

958
01:07:11,695 --> 01:07:14,295
Now, <i> of time and the river</i>
stopped when I met aline.

959
01:07:14,297 --> 01:07:15,530
I'll have to write
about that next.

960
01:07:15,532 --> 01:07:17,799
She won't like it.
She'll love it!

961
01:07:17,801 --> 01:07:19,768
It'll make her immortal.

962
01:07:24,040 --> 01:07:27,242
Oh, Max,
look at this.

963
01:07:27,244 --> 01:07:29,144
What's happening
to our country, Max?

964
01:07:33,482 --> 01:07:36,284
It's so frivolous.
What?

965
01:07:36,286 --> 01:07:38,820
What I do.
Writing books.

966
01:07:38,822 --> 01:07:41,189
These folks
will never read.

967
01:07:41,191 --> 01:07:44,192
Telling my life story
like it's important
to them.

968
01:07:44,194 --> 01:07:45,493
These people
are starving.

969
01:07:51,501 --> 01:07:52,801
Hey, come with me.

970
01:07:55,438 --> 01:07:56,304
Come on.

971
01:08:06,382 --> 01:08:08,083
You have got
to be kidding me.

972
01:08:08,085 --> 01:08:09,217
It'll be worth it,
i promise.

973
01:08:10,086 --> 01:08:11,286
Have I ever lied to you?

974
01:08:19,295 --> 01:08:21,229
This would fall under
the general category

975
01:08:21,231 --> 01:08:22,530
of breaking
and entering.

976
01:08:22,532 --> 01:08:24,165
Let's have
an adventure.

977
01:08:34,577 --> 01:08:35,510
Damn!

978
01:08:36,879 --> 01:08:38,446
I don't believe it.

979
01:08:39,281 --> 01:08:40,715
I don't believe it.

980
01:08:54,330 --> 01:08:57,298
Why on earth
are we here?

981
01:08:57,300 --> 01:09:01,236
This is where I first lived
when I came to New York.

982
01:09:01,238 --> 01:09:04,305
This is where I wrote
<i> look homeward, angel.</i>

983
01:09:11,647 --> 01:09:14,682
I would come here
every twilight

984
01:09:17,286 --> 01:09:18,653
and look at the city

985
01:09:20,156 --> 01:09:22,924
and dream of what
my life might be,

986
01:09:22,926 --> 01:09:24,559
till the stars came out.

987
01:09:26,662 --> 01:09:28,296
The stars in the sky.

988
01:09:29,899 --> 01:09:31,633
The lights
in the buildings.

989
01:09:34,436 --> 01:09:36,404
All those lights.

990
01:09:41,610 --> 01:09:45,380
All the power of life.

991
01:09:48,417 --> 01:09:50,185
You're not
frivolous, tom.

992
01:09:53,589 --> 01:09:56,424
I think back in
the caveman days,

993
01:09:56,426 --> 01:10:00,495
our ancestors would
huddle around
the fire at night

994
01:10:02,731 --> 01:10:07,302
and wolves would be
howling in the dark,
just beyond the light.

995
01:10:07,304 --> 01:10:08,970
And one person
would start talking.

996
01:10:11,407 --> 01:10:12,974
And he would
tell a story,

997
01:10:15,211 --> 01:10:16,978
so we wouldn't be so
scared in the dark.

998
01:11:09,565 --> 01:11:11,733
I guess I'll have
to look at the proofs
when I get back.

999
01:11:11,735 --> 01:11:13,268
Is that all right?

1000
01:11:15,671 --> 01:11:17,805
How long?

1001
01:11:17,807 --> 01:11:21,409
Well, if I don't get shot,
a couple of months.

1002
01:11:21,411 --> 01:11:24,012
I'm telling you,
Spain is where
the action's going to be.

1003
01:11:25,714 --> 01:11:26,981
You've already done
a bullfighting book.

1004
01:11:26,983 --> 01:11:29,450
Nah, it's not
bullfighting this time.

1005
01:11:29,452 --> 01:11:31,486
World's gone
beyond that, I'm afraid.

1006
01:11:31,488 --> 01:11:33,454
It's war that's coming.

1007
01:11:33,456 --> 01:11:35,790
And you need
to be there?

1008
01:11:35,792 --> 01:11:38,026
Well, I need
to be somewhere.

1009
01:11:38,028 --> 01:11:40,595
I need to feel the old
<i> lucha por la vida,</i>
you know?

1010
01:11:40,597 --> 01:11:44,732
The struggle for life.
What else is there?

1011
01:11:44,734 --> 01:11:46,434
Hoist her up, boys.
We want to take
a photograph.

1012
01:11:46,436 --> 01:11:47,468
All right,
you heard him.

1013
01:11:52,775 --> 01:11:53,741
So,

1014
01:11:55,978 --> 01:11:58,646
how's the muse
from greater
asheville doing?

1015
01:11:58,648 --> 01:12:01,416
He's writing
a new book,
god help me.

1016
01:12:01,418 --> 01:12:03,384
Did you read
<i> of time and the river?</i>

1017
01:12:03,386 --> 01:12:06,354
Crap.

1018
01:12:06,356 --> 01:12:08,956
The boy has
serious delusions
of importance.

1019
01:12:08,958 --> 01:12:10,892
And he's been mouthing off
to the press too much.

1020
01:12:10,894 --> 01:12:14,329
Tell him to shut the hell up
and stick to his pencil.

1021
01:12:14,331 --> 01:12:16,764
Well, you know tom,
he's exuberant.

1022
01:12:16,766 --> 01:12:18,766
Bullshit.
He's starting to believe
what they say about him.

1023
01:12:18,768 --> 01:12:20,902
Same thing that happened
to Fitzgerald.

1024
01:12:20,904 --> 01:12:22,937
Gets to hear
he's the great man
of letters so many times,

1025
01:12:22,939 --> 01:12:24,972
he starts to believe it.

1026
01:12:24,974 --> 01:12:27,008
Then he's got
to live up to it and
then he stops writing.

1027
01:12:27,010 --> 01:12:29,811
Tom has to write,
it's in his blood.

1028
01:12:29,813 --> 01:12:32,547
Well, they said
the same thing about
Scott five years ago.

1029
01:12:32,549 --> 01:12:35,383
Most elegant writer
i ever knew.

1030
01:12:35,385 --> 01:12:35,383
Now the poor
son of a bitch

1031
01:12:35,385 --> 01:12:38,820
can't string
five words together
to save his own life.

1032
01:12:41,523 --> 01:12:43,925
You know tom
will leave you soon.

1033
01:12:43,927 --> 01:12:45,393
I don't think so.

1034
01:12:46,895 --> 01:12:49,097
You don't think
those bastards
at Harper's and MacMillan

1035
01:12:49,099 --> 01:12:51,499
aren't pouring poison
in his ear already?

1036
01:12:52,735 --> 01:12:54,769
Tom won't listen.

1037
01:12:54,771 --> 01:12:56,604
You saw the dedication
in <i> time and the river.</i>

1038
01:12:56,606 --> 01:12:57,739
Yeah, I did.

1039
01:12:59,475 --> 01:13:02,410
A bit like something
on a tombstone.

1040
01:13:02,412 --> 01:13:05,146
Come on,
let's take a photo
with your catch.

1041
01:13:05,148 --> 01:13:06,647
I'll get him mounted
and send him to you.

1042
01:13:16,992 --> 01:13:20,661
Our daughter's going
gangbusters at vassar,
she, uh...

1043
01:13:20,663 --> 01:13:23,097
She seems to have
developed an affection
for drama.

1044
01:13:23,099 --> 01:13:24,799
She might even
be an actress.

1045
01:13:26,435 --> 01:13:27,735
She wants to talk
to you about it, Louise.

1046
01:13:27,737 --> 01:13:29,604
Oh, I would love to.

1047
01:13:31,940 --> 01:13:33,641
That must be tom.
I'll get it.

1048
01:13:36,612 --> 01:13:38,679
It's tom, honey.
He's come to see you.

1049
01:13:41,750 --> 01:13:44,452
Come on, Maxwell!
Let me in, now.

1050
01:13:46,122 --> 01:13:48,156
- Tom, easy.
- Where is Scott?

1051
01:13:48,158 --> 01:13:49,590
You might have waited
to start drinking.

1052
01:13:49,592 --> 01:13:50,758
I... I have
to see Scott.

1053
01:13:50,760 --> 01:13:52,560
Tom.

1054
01:13:52,562 --> 01:13:54,929
Scott. Scott!
Tom! Look at me.

1055
01:13:54,931 --> 01:13:56,931
Zelda's just out
of the hospital
and she's not well,

1056
01:13:56,933 --> 01:13:58,199
so for god's sake,
don't start in.

1057
01:13:58,201 --> 01:14:00,568
Listen to you.
I'm not some
rude mechanical.

1058
01:14:01,770 --> 01:14:04,939
Scott!
You old bastard.
Tom!

1059
01:14:04,941 --> 01:14:07,608
I tried to tell that
to Max. I mean...

1060
01:14:07,610 --> 01:14:09,977
Tell me, Scott.
Does...

1061
01:14:09,979 --> 01:14:12,814
Does he...
Does he make you
take a lot out?

1062
01:14:12,816 --> 01:14:13,714
He doesn't make me
do anything.

1063
01:14:15,918 --> 01:14:19,687
Well, does he
"advise" you
to take a lot out?

1064
01:14:21,857 --> 01:14:22,690
We're different
writers, tom.

1065
01:14:24,026 --> 01:14:25,126
How's that?

1066
01:14:26,762 --> 01:14:27,795
I don't write
such long books.

1067
01:14:31,133 --> 01:14:32,700
Don't or can't?
Tom!

1068
01:14:32,702 --> 01:14:34,202
Just say it,
Scotty.

1069
01:14:34,204 --> 01:14:36,838
There's no shame
in writing short,

1070
01:14:36,840 --> 01:14:40,141
though I think
you've taken it
a bit too far.

1071
01:14:40,143 --> 01:14:42,844
I mean, come on.

1072
01:14:42,846 --> 01:14:44,612
Are you gonna write
another novel? Hmm?

1073
01:14:47,984 --> 01:14:50,084
Max, I hear you finally
went fishing with Ernest.

1074
01:14:50,086 --> 01:14:52,153
Yes, in the wilds
of darkest key west.

1075
01:14:52,155 --> 01:14:53,688
Don't ignore me.
That's enough.

1076
01:14:53,690 --> 01:14:57,692
Don't pretend
I'm not here.
Jesus Christ!

1077
01:14:57,694 --> 01:15:01,929
I know goddamn well
you ain't written
a word in years.

1078
01:15:01,931 --> 01:15:04,599
Don't blame me
for that.

1079
01:15:04,601 --> 01:15:07,168
Come on, get up!
What? What? Why?

1080
01:15:07,170 --> 01:15:08,503
- You're leaving.
- Where are we going?

1081
01:15:08,505 --> 01:15:11,205
- Get out.
- Why?

1082
01:15:11,207 --> 01:15:12,607
It's all right,
my sweetheart,
it's all right.

1083
01:15:12,609 --> 01:15:14,108
Stay calm.
It's all right.

1084
01:15:17,613 --> 01:15:19,780
You should tell him
to put her away somewhere

1085
01:15:19,782 --> 01:15:19,780
and get back to work.

1086
01:15:22,084 --> 01:15:24,852
He... he's probably
past it now.

1087
01:15:24,854 --> 01:15:26,554
Couldn't make
a whole book,

1088
01:15:26,556 --> 01:15:29,156
but he's still
got some talent
around the edges.

1089
01:15:30,626 --> 01:15:33,594
Faded grandeur,
i suppose you'd call it.

1090
01:15:33,596 --> 01:15:35,062
Or he'd call it.
But that...

1091
01:15:35,064 --> 01:15:36,597
Would you shut up?

1092
01:15:38,967 --> 01:15:40,601
It amazes me, still,

1093
01:15:40,603 --> 01:15:42,937
after all these years,
how cruel you can be.

1094
01:15:42,939 --> 01:15:45,039
I... I'm only
being honest.

1095
01:15:45,041 --> 01:15:48,576
Did you ever
once try to imagine
how it is for Scott?

1096
01:15:48,578 --> 01:15:50,578
Why...
Why would I?

1097
01:15:50,580 --> 01:15:52,179
How many words
did you write today?

1098
01:15:54,316 --> 01:15:56,617
What?
How many words
did you write today?

1099
01:15:59,221 --> 01:16:01,689
Maybe 5,000.

1100
01:16:01,691 --> 01:16:03,157
Scott wrote
maybe 100.

1101
01:16:03,159 --> 01:16:05,860
If today was a good day.
If today was a great day.

1102
01:16:05,862 --> 01:16:07,728
And he needs to write
as much as you do.

1103
01:16:07,730 --> 01:16:09,230
He fights
over every word.

1104
01:16:09,232 --> 01:16:10,932
Then, he should
fight more.

1105
01:16:10,934 --> 01:16:13,334
His wife
is going mad!

1106
01:16:13,336 --> 01:16:16,103
Nobody cares about
what he writes or even
remembers him anymore.

1107
01:16:16,105 --> 01:16:17,972
Can you imagine
what that's like?

1108
01:16:17,974 --> 01:16:20,308
Don't blame me
for his weakness.

1109
01:16:20,310 --> 01:16:21,943
It hurts me to
see you so cruel.

1110
01:16:23,745 --> 01:16:25,713
So I've disappointed you,
yet again.

1111
01:16:25,715 --> 01:16:28,115
Yes, very much.

1112
01:16:28,117 --> 01:16:30,585
Well, I'm sorry
I'm not decent enough

1113
01:16:30,587 --> 01:16:33,254
for your fine dinner parties
and your fine friends.

1114
01:16:33,256 --> 01:16:36,257
But before
you drag me out
to the woodshed,

1115
01:16:36,259 --> 01:16:38,359
I think you ought to look
at who's giving the lesson.

1116
01:16:38,361 --> 01:16:40,628
Am I supposed to
grow up like you?

1117
01:16:40,630 --> 01:16:42,597
No, tom, but you're
supposed to grow up.

1118
01:16:43,231 --> 01:16:44,632
How dare you?

1119
01:16:46,602 --> 01:16:49,704
You, of all people.
You, of all goddamn people!

1120
01:16:49,706 --> 01:16:51,772
You're nothing
but a coward!

1121
01:16:51,774 --> 01:16:53,908
Stuck in that
sterile little office.

1122
01:16:53,910 --> 01:16:56,744
Every beautiful thing
in you stunted.

1123
01:16:56,746 --> 01:17:01,115
You don't have
the first idea
what it is to be alive!

1124
01:17:01,117 --> 01:17:02,917
You don't know
what it is to wake up

1125
01:17:02,919 --> 01:17:06,120
and grab hold
of life every day
and fight with it.

1126
01:17:06,122 --> 01:17:08,689
You're just so
goddamn scared to live.

1127
01:17:08,691 --> 01:17:10,291
There are other
ways to live!

1128
01:17:12,027 --> 01:17:14,161
There's loving your children
and seeing them grow up right.

1129
01:17:15,731 --> 01:17:18,099
There's providing
for your family.

1130
01:17:18,101 --> 01:17:21,002
There's doing work
that's important and
giving to other people.

1131
01:17:21,004 --> 01:17:23,070
That's enough.
No, I've taken
your abuse

1132
01:17:23,072 --> 01:17:25,873
'cause I told
myself you were worth it.
That the work was worth it.

1133
01:17:25,875 --> 01:17:27,875
But god help anyone
who loves you, tom.

1134
01:17:27,877 --> 01:17:29,710
Because for all
your talk

1135
01:17:29,712 --> 01:17:31,679
and all your millions
of beautiful words,

1136
01:17:31,681 --> 01:17:35,383
you haven't the slightest
idea of what it means
to be alive.

1137
01:17:35,385 --> 01:17:37,718
To look into
another person's eyes
and ache for him.

1138
01:17:40,288 --> 01:17:42,990
I hope someday
you will.

1139
01:17:42,992 --> 01:17:46,327
And then maybe
all your words will be
worth five of Scott's.

1140
01:18:06,682 --> 01:18:08,449
<i> Max thinks</i>
<i> he created me.</i>
<i> You know that?</i>

1141
01:18:08,451 --> 01:18:10,818
<i> Like</i> pygmalion.

1142
01:18:10,820 --> 01:18:14,855
<i> He thinks... he thinks</i>
<i> he found this ugly lump</i>
<i> of Carolina Clay</i>

1143
01:18:14,857 --> 01:18:17,091
<i> and molded it into me.</i>

1144
01:18:19,161 --> 01:18:20,728
They say
i don't even write
my own books.

1145
01:18:20,730 --> 01:18:22,296
They say I can't
write my own books.

1146
01:18:22,298 --> 01:18:24,999
It's all because of Max
and his brilliant editing.

1147
01:18:25,001 --> 01:18:26,400
I hear it
everywhere I go.

1148
01:18:26,402 --> 01:18:28,369
Wouldn't I be lost
without Max?

1149
01:18:28,371 --> 01:18:31,872
What would I do without
the great Maxwell Perkins?

1150
01:18:34,743 --> 01:18:35,843
So he finally
stood up to you.

1151
01:18:37,979 --> 01:18:38,946
Good for him.

1152
01:18:41,183 --> 01:18:44,485
You wouldn't believe how much
the folks at Harper's offered
me for my new book.

1153
01:18:44,487 --> 01:18:47,021
There it is.

1154
01:18:49,024 --> 01:18:51,425
I told them no.

1155
01:18:51,427 --> 01:18:52,393
You told them maybe.

1156
01:18:53,428 --> 01:18:55,062
You tell everyone maybe.

1157
01:18:58,900 --> 01:19:00,201
And now you're going
to tell them yes.

1158
01:19:06,508 --> 01:19:10,111
Hey, I'm thinking
of taking a trip.

1159
01:19:10,113 --> 01:19:13,314
A vacation, like.
Buying an old car
and just driving off.

1160
01:19:13,316 --> 01:19:14,915
Maybe see California.

1161
01:19:16,184 --> 01:19:18,252
All those
sun-kissed locales.

1162
01:19:22,491 --> 01:19:23,891
Why don't you come?

1163
01:19:24,292 --> 01:19:26,861
I mean it.

1164
01:19:26,863 --> 01:19:29,830
Let's hit the road
and have some fun again.

1165
01:19:29,832 --> 01:19:31,398
You and me.

1166
01:19:31,400 --> 01:19:32,967
Like it used to be.

1167
01:19:40,442 --> 01:19:44,912
No one else in
the world even exists.

1168
01:19:47,082 --> 01:19:50,217
Mmm... we're in our
own private cathedral.

1169
01:19:56,291 --> 01:19:58,526
Doesn't that sound like
a momentous journey?

1170
01:20:01,263 --> 01:20:02,930
You need
to spend time alone.

1171
01:20:07,469 --> 01:20:09,303
I'm a writer.

1172
01:20:09,305 --> 01:20:12,239
All I do
is spend time alone.

1173
01:20:12,241 --> 01:20:16,510
No, you spend time
with your characters.
You've never been alone.

1174
01:20:16,512 --> 01:20:19,446
First you had your family,
then you had me,
then you had Max.

1175
01:20:19,448 --> 01:20:21,482
You need
to spend time alone.

1176
01:20:23,585 --> 01:20:25,886
You need to look
at how you move
through your life.

1177
01:20:27,589 --> 01:20:29,223
You hurt me.

1178
01:20:31,526 --> 01:20:34,228
You're going to hurt Max.
You shouldn't hurt
anyone else.

1179
01:20:37,299 --> 01:20:41,035
Human beings
aren't fiction.

1180
01:20:41,037 --> 01:20:43,437
You have no idea
what I had to go through

1181
01:20:43,439 --> 01:20:45,339
to get to where
i am now.

1182
01:20:47,475 --> 01:20:48,976
So I can look at you

1183
01:20:50,412 --> 01:20:51,445
and feel

1184
01:20:52,848 --> 01:20:54,114
nothing.

1185
01:21:07,429 --> 01:21:08,996
You know the way out.

1186
01:21:39,961 --> 01:21:42,096
The last time
i saw my father,

1187
01:21:45,066 --> 01:21:47,468
I was standing
at a train window,

1188
01:21:47,470 --> 01:21:49,103
when I went north
to college.

1189
01:21:52,407 --> 01:21:54,308
He just got
smaller and smaller

1190
01:21:56,344 --> 01:21:57,611
as we pulled away,

1191
01:22:01,549 --> 01:22:03,350
until I couldn't
see him anymore.

1192
01:22:10,358 --> 01:22:14,128
That train
carried me to my life.

1193
01:22:16,698 --> 01:22:18,599
Beyond the hills
and over the rivers.

1194
01:22:21,703 --> 01:22:23,470
And always,
the rivers run.

1195
01:22:32,180 --> 01:22:34,581
Sometimes they flow
away from my father

1196
01:22:34,583 --> 01:22:37,685
and sometimes they
flow back to his door.

1197
01:22:44,559 --> 01:22:46,660
I have to prove
i can do it
by myself.

1198
01:22:50,031 --> 01:22:51,265
Then prove it.

1199
01:23:51,192 --> 01:23:53,093
Scott.

1200
01:23:53,095 --> 01:23:56,430
I know it was
a while ago
but I'm sorry.

1201
01:23:56,432 --> 01:23:58,132
I was a damn brute.

1202
01:23:58,134 --> 01:24:00,467
I wouldn't blame you
if you slammed
the door in my face.

1203
01:24:00,469 --> 01:24:04,705
You don't know how sorry
i am for talking to you
and Zelda like that.

1204
01:24:04,707 --> 01:24:07,708
Please, say
you forgive me.

1205
01:24:07,710 --> 01:24:09,443
Believe it or not,
I've been drunk
myself once or twice.

1206
01:24:12,581 --> 01:24:13,680
Thank you.

1207
01:24:19,254 --> 01:24:22,222
I'm still a bit
of a washout
as a screenwriter.

1208
01:24:22,224 --> 01:24:24,658
I just can't make
the grade as a hack.

1209
01:24:24,660 --> 01:24:27,828
Even that
requires a certain
practiced excellence.

1210
01:24:29,697 --> 01:24:32,433
I'm mighty glad
to see you, Scott.

1211
01:24:32,435 --> 01:24:34,068
I've been rambling around
for months now.

1212
01:24:35,403 --> 01:24:38,072
Haven't had anybody
to talk to about work.

1213
01:24:38,840 --> 01:24:41,175
Ah. Work.

1214
01:24:41,177 --> 01:24:42,810
I mean,
who better to talk to?

1215
01:24:42,812 --> 01:24:46,113
The man who created
something immortal.

1216
01:24:46,115 --> 01:24:49,183
More and more,
i trouble myself with that.

1217
01:24:49,818 --> 01:24:52,586
"The legacy."

1218
01:24:52,588 --> 01:24:56,790
Will anyone care about
Thomas wolfe in
100 years? Ten years?

1219
01:24:56,792 --> 01:25:00,694
When I was young,
